    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA22-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu varaivu malinta tōḻi talaimakaṭkuc colliyatu. (EV: talaivaṉ varaintu koḷḷa vantaṉaḷ eṉṟu makiḻntu talaivikkut tōḻi kūṟāniṟpatu.)</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the confidante who rejoiced in marriage said to HER. (EV: What the confidante was telling HER after rejoicing that she would come when HE took [her] in marriage.)</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA22">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            koṭicci kākku maṭukkaṟ paintiṉai</l>
<l>            muntuviḷai peruṅkural koṇṭa manti</l>
<l>            kallāk kaṭuvaṉoṭu nalvarai yēṟi</l>
<l>            yaṅkai niṟaiya ñemiṭik koṇṭutaṉ</l>
<l>            ṟiraiyaṇaṟ koṭuṅkavu ṇiṟaiya mukki </l>
<l>            vāṉpeya ṉaṉainta puṟatta nōṉpiyar</l>
<l>            kaiyū ṇirukkaiyiṟ ṟōṉṟu nāṭaṉ</l>
<l>            vantaṉaṉ vāḻi tōḻi yulakaṅ</l>
<l>            kayaṅka ṇaṟṟa paitaṟu kālaip</l>
<l>            pīḷoṭu tiraṅkiya nelliṟku </l>
<l>            naḷḷeṉ yāmattu maḻaipoḻin tāṅkē.</l>
        </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>            The man from a land,</l>
<l rend="indent">where the she-monkey that has taken the big ears ripening first on</l>
<l rend="indent2">the mountain side's fresh millet guarded by the creeper-woman,</l>
<l rend="indent">climbing the good mountain with its unlearned male</l>
<l rend="indent">[and] pressing [the ear] out for herself(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ñemiti koṇṭu</term>: can <term xml:lang="ta">koṇṭu</term> here be understood as an auxiliary, i.e. as a reflexive similar to the modern language?</note> so that its palm is filled</l>
<l rend="indent">[and] gulping [it down],</l>
<l rend="indent">for [its] wrinkled warm curved cheek to become full,</l>
<l rend="indent">appears like an ascetic sitting food in hand<note place="foot">Or we read the variant <term xml:lang="ta">taiyūṇ</term>: "[having] food in the month of Tai".</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent2">back become wet by the raining from the sky,</l>
<l rend="indent3">– he came, oh friend,</l>
<l rend="indent">like rain pouring at deepest midnight</l>
<l rend="indent2">on the paddy that had withered with [its] shoots,</l>
<l rend="indent3">in a time when the green subsides, as [water] subsided</l>
<l rend="indent4">in the ponds of the world.<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">aṟṟa</term>: actually here the peyareccam is slightly awkward. We would expect to see rather an absolutive (with change of subject, and aspectual mark of anteriority) or an infinitive (correct as it naturally changes subject, but without aspectual impact).</note></l>
        </lg>
